  "prompt": "Which parts of Japan were settled last?",
  "response": "The settlement of Japan primarily followed a south-to-north trajectory, with the northernmost regions being among the last to be settled. Hokkaido, the northernmost island of Japan, was one of the last areas to be fully settled and developed. Historically, the indigenous Ainu people inhabited Hokkaido, but large-scale Japanese settlement and development did not occur until the late 19th century during the Meiji era. This was part of a government initiative to integrate Hokkaido more fully into Japan and to exploit its resources. Consequently, Hokkaido was relatively late in terms of widespread Japanese settlement compared to other regions of Japan.",
